The Lombok Annotations
The first four annotations—@Data, @Builder, @NoArgsConstructor, and @AllArgsConstructor—are from the Project Lombok library. 
They are designed to dramatically reduce "boilerplate" code that Java developers traditionally had to type by hand.

By adding these annotations at the top of the Order POJO, Lombok automatically manipulates the compiled Java byte-code to inject the following for us:

@Data: This is a powerful shortcut annotation. It automatically generates all the get() and set() methods for every field, alongside toString(), equals(), and hashCode() methods.

@Builder: This generates the implementation for the "Builder Design Pattern" for the class. 
It allows us to construct the object cleanly and logically in our code (e.g., Order.builder().customerName("Alice").build(); 
instead of chaining endless .setCustomerName("Alice") statements).

@NoArgsConstructor: This generates an empty, default constructor (public Order() {}). 
This is absolutely required by Spring Boot.
When Spring receives a JSON payload from a POST request, its internal JSON parser (Jackson) requires an empty constructor to create the object first before it assigns values to the fields!

@AllArgsConstructor: Generates a constructor that accepts every single field at once. The @Builder annotation actually requires this to operate smoothly behind the scenes.



@NotNull vs @NotBlank
These two are part of the Jakarta Bean Validation specification, and choosing between them is incredibly important to secure your API endpoints:

@NotNull: This simply checks that the object reference isn't literally null.

Best for: Dates, Numbers, and Enums. If someone sends an empty JSON {} without an amount, @NotNull on the amount field will catch it.
Warning: If you put @NotNull on a String, it will accept an empty string ("") or even whitespace ("   "), because a blank object is still technically "not a null pointer".

@NotBlank: This handles the "blank text" loophole perfectly. It verifies that a String is not null, AND that its trimmed length is strictly greater than zero.
Best for: Strings (like customerName). It prevents users from sending a JSON request with "customerName": "    ", catching it instantly!

